-- Hyundai Heavy, ICBC, Posco, Shinhan, TSMC: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 2010-10-28T18:25:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/hyundai-heavy-icbc-posco-shinhan-tsmc-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  Asian trading , excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  China Telecom Corp.  (728 HK): The country’s biggest fixed-
line carrier posted third-quarter profit that beat analyst
estimates as the company’s mobile-phone unit added subscribers.
Profit excluding gains from connection fees rose 27 percent to
3.78 billion yuan ($565 million) from 2.98 billion yuan a year
earlier, the Beijing-based company said in a statement on its
website. Income was projected to be 3.54 billion yuan, according
to the median estimate of five analysts surveyed by Bloomberg
News. The stock added 0.2 percent to HK$4.15.  GMA Network Inc.  (GMA7 PM): The second-largest Philippine
television and radio broadcaster said third-quarter net income
decreased 26 percent to 583 million pesos ($14 million) as major
advertisers cut spending. The company said it expects to meet
its profit target for the year. The stock fell 3.7 percent to
7.35 pesos.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co.  (009540 KS): The world’s
largest shipbuilder boosted third-quarter profit by 62 percent
to 863.4 billion won ($768 million) as it built more offshore
platforms and power plants. That beat the 716.9 billion won
average of 22 analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg. Sales
gained 7 percent to 5.33 trillion won. The shares fell 0.3
percent to 367,000 won.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (1398 HK): The
world’s largest lender by market value posted a 27 percent gain
in third-quarter profit to 42.6 billion yuan ($6.4 billion) on
an increase in demand for credit as prospects for economic
growth improved. That was in line with the 42.8 billion yuan
median estimate of nine analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. The
shares added 0.7 percent to HK$6.24.  IPVG Corp.  (IP PM): IP Converge Data Center Inc., the
company’s information technology and telecommunications unit,
won approval from the nation’s stock exchange to sell 45.57
million shares at 8.80 pesos apiece in an initial public
offering in November, a stock exchange filing showed. IPVG
gained 0.5 percent to 1.86 pesos.  Posco  (005490 KS): The world’s third-biggest steelmaker by
output said it is reviewing a possible purchase of Norway’s
Elkem ASA, a maker of solar-grade silicon and special alloys.
The company has yet to make a decision, Pohang, South Korea-
based Posco said in a regulatory filing after the Korea Exchange
sought a clarification on reports about a potential purchase.
Posco dropped 1.3 percent to 466,000 won.  Shinhan Financial Group Co.  (055550 KS): South Korea’s
largest financial company by market value said third-quarter
profit increased 33 percent to 652 billion won as sales of
stakes in other companies offset higher bad-loan provisions.
That beat the 602.1 billion won average of 15 analyst estimates
compiled by Bloomberg in the past 28 days. The shares dropped
0.2 percent to 43,950 won.  Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co.  (2330 TT): The
world’s largest contract manufacturer of chips posted a fourth
straight quarter of profit growth after demand for smartphones
helped sales beat its forecast. Third-quarter net income climbed
54 percent to NT$46.9 billion ($1.5 billion) from NT$30.6
billion a year earlier, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company said
in a statement. TSMC gained 1.1 percent to NT$62.7.  Tenaga Nasional Bhd.  (TNB MK): Malaysia’s biggest power
producer said fourth-quarter profit  more than doubled to 388.4
million ringgit ($125 million) after a strengthening ringgit
reduced its foreign-currency debt and economic expansion boosted
electricity demand. Tenaga added 0.5 percent to 8.87 ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
